# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1949-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1949 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the first edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1949-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in Prague, Czechoslovakia from 10 to 18 September 1949.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1949-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The tournament was played in a single round-robin format, with all teams placed in a single group.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1950-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1950 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the second edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1950-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in Sofia, Bulgaria from 14 to 22 October 1950.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1951-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1951 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the third edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1951-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in Paris, France from 15 to 22 September 1951.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1951-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The tournament was played in two different stages.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1951-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] In the first stage, the six participants were divided into two groups of three teams.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1951-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The winners and runners-up of each group advanced to a second stage of a single group containing four teams.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1951-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] All groups in both stages played a single round-robin format.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1955-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1955 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the fourth edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1955-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in Bucharest, Romania from 15 to 24 June 1955.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1958-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1958 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the fifth edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1958-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in Czechoslovakia from 30 August to 10 September 1958.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1958-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] In the first stage, the twelve participants were divided into four groups of three teams.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1958-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] In the second stage, two groups were formed, one containing the winners and runners-up from all first stage groups (eight teams in total) to contest the tournament title.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1958-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] A second group was formed by the last placed teams of first stage groups (four teams) which played for position places (9th to 12th).
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1963-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1963 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the sixth edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1963-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in several cities in Romania from 22 October to 2 November 1963, with the final round held in Constanţa.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1963-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] In the first stage, the thirteen participants were divided into four groups (three groups of three teams and one group of four teams).
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1963-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] A second group was formed by the remaining five teams which played for position places (9th to 13th).
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1967-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1967 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the seventh edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1967-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in several cities in Turkey from 22 October to 8 November 1967, with the final round held in İzmir.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1967-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] In the first stage, the fifteen participants were divided into four groups (three groups of four teams and one group of three teams).
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1967-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] A second group was formed by the remaining seven teams which played for position places (9th to 15th).
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The **1995 Women's European Volleyball Championship** was the 19th edition of the event, organised by Europe's governing volleyball body, the Confédération Européenne de Volleyball.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] It was hosted in Arnhem and Groningen, Netherlands from 23 September to 1 October 1995.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The two finalists qualified for the 1995 FIVB Women's World Cup.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] In the first stage, the twelve participants were divided in two groups of six teams each.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] A single round-robin format was played within each group to determine the teams' group position.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The second stage of the tournament consisted of two sets of semifinals to determine the tournament final ranking.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The group stage firsts and seconds played the semifinals for 1st to 4th place, group stage thirds and fourths played the 5th to 8th place semifinals and the remaining four teams which finished group stages as fifth and sixth ended all tied in final ranking at 9th place.
[src:1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship/1995-women-s-european-volleyball-championship] The pairing of the semifinals was made so teams played against the opposite group teams which finished in a different position (1st played against 2nd, 3rd played against 4th).
